message.content: Bill Clinton was the President of the United States in 1996. He served as the 42nd President from January 20, 1993, to January 20, 2001. During his presidency, he focused on issues such as healthcare reform, economic growth, and foreign policy. Clinton was re-elected in 1996, defeating Republican candidate Bob Dole. Some of the key events that occurred during his presidency include the signing of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), the implementation of welfare reform, and the bombing of Kosovo. Clinton's presidency was also marked by several scandals, including the Monica Lewinsky affair, which led to his impeachment by the House of Representatives in 1998. However, he was acquitted by the Senate and served out the remainder of his term. Despite the controversies, Clinton is regarded as one of the most successful presidents in modern American history, with a strong economy and low unemployment rates during his time in office.|im_end|>
